<subSubSection pageNumber="371" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="371">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="371">Note:</emphasis>
Linnaeus cited, as a synonym, an account of the species published by Arduino in 1764, in which the binomial 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Cacalia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="371">C. linifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Ard. was adopted. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Linnaeus’">Linnaeus'</normalizedToken>
name is therefore illegitimate. Johnson (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="371">Univ. Kansas Sci. Bull.</emphasis>
48: 239. 1968) wrongly cited this as &quot; 
<taxonomicName authority="L." authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1767" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Cacalia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="371">Cacalia linifolia</emphasis>
L.
</taxonomicName>
&quot; as published in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="371">Mant. Pl.</emphasis>
: 109. 1767, though the epithet clearly came from Arduino. Johnson stated that he had seen a photo &quot;of type from Linnean herbarium&quot;. Presumably this is likely to have been 976.2 (LINN) - 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="371">Arduino 20 -</emphasis>
with the epithets 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“fruticulosa”">&quot;fruticulosa&quot;</normalizedToken>
, and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“suffruticosa”">&quot;suffruticosa&quot;</normalizedToken>
added by Smith. However, further study would be necessary to establish its link with 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Arduino’s">Arduino's</normalizedToken>
name.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
